## Why a Dedicated Serilog Part

Default logging can carry correlation scope, but Serilog gives you tighter control over:

1. property naming discipline,
2. event shape consistency,
3. sink-specific output formats,
4. query ergonomics in log backends.

If your team debugs from structured events daily, this is worth doing explicitly.

## 1. Configure Serilog with Context Enrichment

Start by enabling context enrichment so properties pushed into `LogContext` appear in every log event within that scope.

```csharp
using Serilog;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

Log.Logger = new LoggerConfiguration()
    .ReadFrom.Configuration(builder.Configuration)
    .Enrich.FromLogContext()
    .Enrich.WithProperty("Service", "work-orders-api")
    .WriteTo.Console()
    .CreateLogger();

builder.Host.UseSerilog();
```

`Enrich.FromLogContext()` is the key line. Without it, your correlation scope will not flow into output events.

### Conceptual Note: `PushProperty` and `ILogger` Scopes

At a conceptual level, `LogContext.PushProperty("CorrelationId", value)` behaves like opening a logging scope that carries a dictionary entry for `CorrelationId` across all log events in that ambient execution flow.

Internally, Serilog keeps these values in its ambient `LogContext` and `Enrich.FromLogContext()` copies them onto each event. In the `Microsoft.Extensions.Logging` world, the closest equivalent is `BeginScope` with key-value pairs:

```csharp
using (logger.BeginScope(new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    ["CorrelationId"] = correlationId
}))
{
    logger.LogInformation("Inside correlation scope");
}
```

So while `PushProperty` is Serilog-native (not literally calling `BeginScope`), it is functionally the same idea: scope-bound properties flowing through `ILogger`-style logging pipelines.

## 2. Add Correlation Middleware for Serilog

At ingress, normalize the correlation id and push it into `LogContext`.

```csharp
using Serilog.Context;
using System.Diagnostics;

public sealed class SerilogCorrelationMiddleware
{
    private const string CorrelationHeader = "X-Correlation-Id";
    private const string CorrelationItemKey = "CorrelationId";

    private readonly RequestDelegate _next;

    public SerilogCorrelationMiddleware(RequestDelegate next)
    {
        _next = next;
    }

    public async Task InvokeAsync(HttpContext context)
    {
        var incoming = context.Request.Headers[CorrelationHeader].ToString();
        var correlationId = IsValid(incoming)
            ? incoming
            : Guid.NewGuid().ToString("N");

        var traceId = Activity.Current?.TraceId.ToString() ?? string.Empty;

        context.Items[CorrelationItemKey] = correlationId;
        context.Response.Headers[CorrelationHeader] = correlationId;

        using (LogContext.PushProperty("CorrelationId", correlationId))
        using (LogContext.PushProperty("TraceId", traceId))
        {
            await _next(context);
        }
    }

    private static bool IsValid(string value)
    {
        if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(value) || value.Length > 64)
        {
            return false;
        }

        return value.All(ch => char.IsLetterOrDigit(ch) || ch is '-' or '_');
    }
}
```

Register it early in the pipeline:

```csharp
var app = builder.Build();

app.UseMiddleware<SerilogCorrelationMiddleware>();

app.MapControllers();
app.Run();
```

## 3. Access Correlation Data Without HttpContext Leaks

Use an accessor so application services stay testable.

```csharp
public interface ICorrelationAccessor
{
    string GetCorrelationId();
}

public sealed class HttpCorrelationAccessor : ICorrelationAccessor
{
    private readonly IHttpContextAccessor _httpContextAccessor;

    public HttpCorrelationAccessor(IHttpContextAccessor httpContextAccessor)
    {
        _httpContextAccessor = httpContextAccessor;
    }

    public string GetCorrelationId()
    {
        return _httpContextAccessor.HttpContext?.Items["CorrelationId"] as string ?? string.Empty;
    }
}
```

Registration:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpContextAccessor();
builder.Services.AddScoped<ICorrelationAccessor, HttpCorrelationAccessor>();
```

## 4. Propagate Correlation on Outbound HttpClient Calls

Keep propagation automatic with a delegating handler.

```csharp
public sealed class SerilogCorrelationHeaderHandler : DelegatingHandler
{
    private readonly ICorrelationAccessor _correlationAccessor;

    public SerilogCorrelationHeaderHandler(ICorrelationAccessor correlationAccessor)
    {
        _correlationAccessor = correlationAccessor;
    }

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        var correlationId = _correlationAccessor.GetCorrelationId();
        if (!string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(correlationId))
        {
            request.Headers.Remove("X-Correlation-Id");
            request.Headers.Add("X-Correlation-Id", correlationId);
        }

        return base.SendAsync(request, cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

```csharp
builder.Services.AddTransient<SerilogCorrelationHeaderHandler>();

builder.Services
    .AddHttpClient<InventoryApiClient>(client =>
    {
        client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://inventory-api.internal/");
    })
    .AddHttpMessageHandler<SerilogCorrelationHeaderHandler>();
```

## 5. Design Event Templates for Queryability

Structured logging fails if templates are inconsistent. Keep message templates stable and put variable data in named properties.

Good:

```csharp
logger.LogInformation(
    "Dispatch created for {WorkOrderId} with {TechnicianId}",
    workOrderId,
    technicianId);
```

Avoid:

```csharp
logger.LogInformation($"Dispatch created for {workOrderId} with {technicianId}");
```

Interpolated strings turn structured fields into plain text in many sinks.

## 6. Example Output Shape

A query-friendly event should look like this:

```json
{
  "Timestamp": "2026-05-05T21:07:11.152Z",
  "Level": "Information",
  "MessageTemplate": "Dispatch created for {WorkOrderId} with {TechnicianId}",
  "Properties": {
    "Service": "work-orders-api",
    "CorrelationId": "wo_8fd2a0f0c2ad4cb8b85c",
    "TraceId": "7b460d4f5e9c2beecf9418a6e9b91095",
    "WorkOrderId": "2a53d241-233f-48f8-a720-b9dd9f41f3a7",
    "TechnicianId": "a1b6cfcf-4f14-4c6f-86cc-4f645df5d1f6"
  }
}
```

This shape supports direct filters like `CorrelationId = ...` and group-by analysis on operation fields.

## 7. Serilog Sink Notes

- Console sink is good for local development and container stdout collection.
- Central sinks (Seq, Elasticsearch-compatible backends, cloud log services) benefit most from structured fields.
- Use per-sink minimum levels to control cost without dropping critical events.

Example configuration snippet:

```json
{
  "Serilog": {
    "MinimumLevel": {
      "Default": "Information",
      "Override": {
        "Microsoft": "Warning",
        "System": "Warning"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## 8. Common Mistakes

- Missing `Enrich.FromLogContext()` so correlation properties never appear.
- Pushing inconsistent property names (`Correlation`, `RequestId`, `Session`) across services.
- Logging sensitive values in scope properties.
- Relying on message text search instead of structured property queries.

## Summary

Serilog makes correlation operationally sharp:

1. enrich once at request start,
2. keep property names fixed,
3. propagate headers automatically,
4. write stable message templates,
5. query by properties, not strings.

That closes the series with a production-ready structured logging foundation for multi-service debugging.